# AI Writing System

## Core Principle

- Do not rely on implicit model memory.
- Store important canon, continuity, and process state in project files.

## Scope

- These rules are global and apply to all books and series in the workspace.
- Book-specific or series-specific rules may define language, genre, tone, POV, pacing, and target chapter length.
- Local book or series rules override global stylistic defaults, but must not break canon consistency inside that project.
- Every active project must behave in one of two modes:
  - `standalone`: one project equals one book.
  - `series`: one project equals a multi-book series with volume-specific subfolders.
- Projects may optionally be grouped to share canon across many stories:
  - A `world` groups several stories (any mix of `standalone` and `series`) that share a setting, magic system, and physics.
  - A `universe` groups several `world`s that share a cosmology and overarching philosophy.
  - Grouping is optional. An ungrouped project that lives directly under `books/<project_id>/` stays fully valid.
  - A `world` and a `universe` are canon containers, not modes. The mode (`standalone` / `series`) is still set per story.

## Structure

- Each project lives under `books/<project_id>/`.
- `standalone` projects store chapter files directly in `chapters/`.
- `series` projects store long-range canon at the project root and active-book material inside `volumes/<book_id>/`.
- Each project maintains memory files in `memory/`.
- `series` projects may additionally maintain volume-local memory inside `volumes/<book_id>/memory/`.
- Role prompts live in `system/prompts/` and are used by workflow stage.
- Agent-specific cross-book mistakes may live in `system/mistakes/` and are read through the matching stage prompt when relevant.

## Required Context

- Before planning, writing, writer cleanup, revising, or updating memory, read the relevant local rules for the active project if they exist.
- Before each workflow stage, read the matching file in `system/prompts/` for that stage.
- Before each workflow stage, read the matching global mistakes file in `system/mistakes/` if it exists.
- Determine the active scope before any stage:
  - `standalone`: the project root is the active scope.
  - `series`: the project root is the series scope and one `volumes/<book_id>/` directory is the active volume scope.
- Determine the grouping of the active project before any stage:
  - ungrouped: the project lives directly under `books/<project_id>/`; no shared canon layers apply.
  - grouped in a `world`: the project lives under `books/<universe_id>/<world_id>/<project_id>/` (or `books/<world_id>/<project_id>/` when there is no universe); the world layer adds shared canon above the story.
  - grouped in a `universe`: the enclosing `world` itself lives under a `universe` that adds another shared canon layer above the world.
- When the active project is grouped, before planning, writing, writer cleanup, revising, or updating memory, also read shared canon top-down, each layer when present:
  - universe-level canon: cosmology and universe rules in the enclosing `<universe_id>/`
  - world-level canon: `world-rules.md`, shared `characters.md` and `timeline.md`, and world rules in the enclosing `<world_id>/`
- A grouped story may add detail but must not contradict the shared canon of its `world` or `universe`. Treat a needed change to shared canon as a cross-story retcon and stop to ask first.
- Before writing, writer cleanup, or revising a chapter in a `standalone` project, read:
  - `outline.md`
  - `characters.md`
  - `memory/state.md` when present (current-truth snapshot)
  - `memory/summaries/` for completed parts when present
  - current-part memory files (`events.md`, `relationships.md`, `foreshadowing.md`)
  - negative-canon ledgers required by local rules when present (e.g. `memory/memory-ledger.md`)
  - previous canon chapter when available
  - approved chapter plan when available
- Before writing, writer cleanup, or revising a chapter in a `series` project, read:
  - series-level `outline.md`
  - series-level `characters.md`
  - series-level `world-rules.md` and `timeline.md` when present
  - series-level relevant memory files
  - active volume `outline.md`
  - active volume `characters.md` and `timeline.md` when present
  - active volume `memory/state.md` when present, part summaries when present, and current-part memory files
  - negative-canon ledgers required by local rules when present
  - previous canon chapter in the active volume when available
  - approved active-volume chapter plan when available
- `memory/events-archive.md` is reference material, not required reading: consult it only to verify a specific old detail.

## Global Constraints

- Do not rewrite full memory files when a targeted update is enough.
- Do not introduce major canon elements without recording them in the appropriate project files.
- Preserve character consistency, world rules, and timeline consistency.
- Treat accepted chapter files and approved revisions as canon unless the user explicitly changes canon.
- In `series` projects, keep series-level canon and volume-level canon distinct instead of collapsing them into one file by habit.
